@startmindmap
* ML-KEM\n(agree on a secret code a quantum computer cannot steal)
** The problem
*** Two people must agree on a secret while everyone listens
*** A spy can record now and crack later
*** Quantum computers will break today's method
** The padlock idea
*** Alice hands out an open padlock (public key)
*** Bob locks a random secret in a box (ciphertext)
*** Only Alice's key opens it
** The padlock a robot cannot pick
*** Secret numbers times a big public grid
*** Add "fuzz" so nobody can work backwards
*** This is the puzzle quantum computers cannot solve
** A dice roll, not a chosen note
*** Bob locks a random number, never a chosen one
*** Nothing for a cheater to craft
** The double-check
*** Alice re-locks the box the same way and compares
*** Match means honest
*** Mismatch: quietly hand back a fake key, never an error
** Three sizes
*** ML-KEM-512 / 768 / 1024
*** Bigger is safer but heavier
*** 768 is the recommended default
** Keeps secrets, does not check who
*** No proof of who sent the padlock
*** Add a signature to know who
*** Often paired with an older lock as a backup
@endmindmap
